ibes, whose members were then systematically swindled out of their private parcels.The publication of Debo's book fundamentally changed the way historians viewed, and wrote about, American Indian history. Writers from Oliver LaFarge, who characterized it as "a work of art," to Vine Deloria, Jr., and Larry McMurtry acknowledge debts to Angie Debo. Fifty years after the book's publication, McMurtry praised Debo's work in the New York Review of Books: "The reader," he wrote, "is pulled along by her strength of mind and power of sympathy."Because the book's findings implicated prominent state politicians and supporters of the University of Oklahoma, the university press there was forced to reject the book in . for fear of libel suits and backlash against the university. Nonetheless, the director of the University of Oklahoma Press at the time, Joseph Brandt, invited Debo to publish her book with Princeton University Press, where he became director in 1938.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aFive Civilized TribesxGovernment relations. 0aIndians of North AmericaxGovernment relations. 0aIndians of North AmericazIndian Territory. 0aIndians of North AmericazOklahoma. 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh  aArdmore.  aAtoka.  aBacone College.  aCarpetbaggers.  aCoffeyville.  aCruce, Lee.  aDaily Oklahoman.  aDawes Commission.  aFederal control of.  aFive Tribes Act.  aForgery.  aFullblood conveyances.  aGovernment, tribal.  aHitchcock.  aIllegal conveyances.  aKee-too-wahs.  aLand tenure.  aLegislature of Oklahoma.  aMcCumber Amendment.  aMixed bloods.  aMuskogee.  aOil.  aPauls Valley Free Lance.  aSells.  aStandard-Sentinel.  aUnenrolled children.  aWagoner.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archiv